Lab 7¶

Introduction¶

We will be doing the event selection optimization to increase the significance of our Higgs measurement for the dataset with lower pT(transverse momentum) samples for this lab.

About the Data¶

The LHC produces around 1 billion events per second which is comparable to the speed of a CPU in a computer. This is great as it means that the computer can process the events - just barely - however the storage required to record an event is around 1 MB which, for 1 billion events, is not feasible. Instead, about 200 MB of data is written per second thus only about 100 to 200 of the 1 billion events are recorded. In order to determine which data to write and which data to throw away a triggering system is put in place - informed by the physical event that is trying to be observed. This system will result in recording events that satisfy a list of criteria. We could imagine one possible criteria would be for the mass of the particle observed to be around 125 Gev/c^2 if we were searching for the Higgs Boson.

Our data set not true data from the LHC ATLAS detector but rather simulated data. We have a total of 100k simulated QCD Background events and 100k Higgs Boson events. Additionally, the data set we will be exploring will only include events that have a high transverse momentum, $pT$, between 1000 and 1200. Provided this data is simulated, our expected yields in the lab are $N_{higgs} = 100$ and $N_{qcd} = 20000$.

$R_{higgs} = 100/100000 = .001$ $R_{qcd} = 20000/100000 = .02$

$yield_{higgs} = N_{higgs} * R_{higgs}$

$yield_{qcd} = N_{qcd} * R_{qcd}$

$N_{higgs}$, number of higgs simulated events

$N_{qcd}$, number of qcd simulated events

Calculating Significance¶

To calculate the significance we will answer the following question:

What is the significance of getting a signal of 20100 (n_higgs + n_qcd) provided a QCD background of poisson distribution with parameter as 20000?

Our background is Poisson distribution so we will use Poisson statistics for the significance calculation.

In [4]:
probability = stats.poisson.sf(20100, 20000)
sig = stats.norm.isf(probability)
sig
Out[4]:
0.7112259282313185

Comparing the exact significance to the approximation¶

The significance of getting 20100 jets is .711

NHiggs/sqrt(NQCD) = 100/sqrt(20000) = 0.707

We can see that the value of the exact significance is very close to the value of the approximation. However they are not exactly the same. This is because according to the Central Limit Theorem when the parameter of the Poisson distribution gets large the Poisson distribution behaves more like a Gaussian distribution with standard deviation equal to the root of the parameter of Poisson distribution.

The parameter for our background Poisson distribution is n_qcd, thus the standard deviation of our approximate Gaussian is sqrt(n_qcd).

Now as the mean of this Poisson distribution, and thus Gaussian distribution is n_qcd we know that our signal n_qcd + n_higgs is simply the mean value of the distribution plus n_higgs.

To get how many standard deviations the n_higgs is from the mean we divide n_higgs by the standard deviation.Thus we get n_higgs/sqrt(n_qcd).

Thusthe value of the exact significance is very close to the value of the approximation.The value does not exactly match as pisson distribution only approaches the Gaussian distribution as its parameter increases it will never be exactly Gaussian distribution.

def plot_stacked(feature):
    bins = 100
    qcd_feature_data = qcd_data[feature]
    higgs_feature_data = higgs_data[feature]
    feature_data = [qcd_data[feature], higgs_data[feature]]
    
    qcd_feature_cut_data = qcd_cut3[feature]
    higgs_feature_cut_data = higgs_cut3[feature]
    feature_cut_data = [qcd_cut3[feature], higgs_cut3[feature]]
    
    plt.suptitle('Stacked QCD background for ' + feature)
    # Without cutting data
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
    plt.hist(feature_data, bins=100, stacked=True, label=['QCD Background counts', 'Higgs counts'])
    plt.title('Stacked QCD background counts and Higgs counts')
    plt.xlabel(f' {feature}')
    plt.ylabel('Event counts')
    plt.legend()
    
    plt.show()
    
    # After slicing
    plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
    plt.hist(feature_cut_data, bins=100, stacked=True, label=['QCD Background counts', 'Higgs counts'])
    plt.title('Stacked QCD background counts and Higgs counts cut at mass')
    plt.xlabel(f' {feature}')
    plt.ylabel('Event counts')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Comparison With Peter T Gwartney's Report¶

My lab partner Peter T Gwartney did a similar analysis on a different set of data. His set of data was once again 100k QCD background events and 100k Higgs Boson events except his events all have a transverse momentum, pT, between 1000 and 1200 where all of my events have a transverse momentum between 250 and 500.His initial significance without any cuts was 1.1282 which was higher than mine. He made several cuts to increase his significance to 4.548.This is slightly lower than 5 which is contrary to mine 5.0959 which is slightly greater than 5.The set of feature cuts found by him were angularity, t1 and t3. The set of differentiating features found by me were t21 and t2.

computing ratio

In [100]:
qcd_base_R = (qcd_base_yield) / (qcd_base_yield + higgs_base_yield) 
higgs_base_R = (higgs_base_yield) / (qcd_base_yield + higgs_base_yield) 
qcd_slice_R = (qcd_sliced_yield) / (qcd_sliced_yield + higgs_sliced_yield)
higgs_slice_R = (higgs_sliced_yield) /(qcd_sliced_yield + higgs_sliced_yield)

function to generate plots

In [105]:
def generate_plot(feature, lumi, lumi_sliced):
    # combined array for plotting
    base_combined = [qcd_data[f'{feature}'], higgs_data[f'{feature}']]
    sliced_combined = [new_cut_qcd[f'{feature}'], new_cut_higgs[f'{feature}']]
    
    # lets also compute the weights to scale the histogram heights by
    base_weights_qcd = np.ones(len(qcd_data)) * qcd_base_R * (len(lumi) / len(qcd_data))
    base_weights_higgs = np.ones(len(higgs_data)) * higgs_base_R * (len(lumi) / len(higgs_data))
    sliced_weights_qcd = np.ones(len(new_cut_qcd)) * qcd_slice_R * (len(lumi_sliced) / len(new_cut_qcd))
    sliced_weights_higgs = np.ones(len(new_cut_higgs)) * higgs_slice_R * (len(lumi_sliced) / len(new_cut_higgs))
    
    #plotting
    plt.subplot(2,1,1)
    plt.hist(base_combined, bins = 50, stacked = True, weights = [base_weights_qcd, base_weights_higgs], label = ['Qcd Background', 'Higgs Data'])
    plt.hist(lumi[f'{feature}'], bins = 50, stacked = True, histtype='step', color='k', linestyle='--', label='Observed Data')
    plt.title("Unsliced Data")
    plt.xlabel(f'{feature}')
    plt.ylabel("Event Counts")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
    
    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    plt.hist(sliced_combined, bins = 50, stacked = True, weights = [sliced_weights_qcd, sliced_weights_higgs], label = ['Qcd Background', 'Higgs Data'])
    plt.hist(lumi_sliced[f'{feature}'], bins = 50, stacked = True, histtype='step', color='k', linestyle='--', label='Observed Data')
    plt.title("Sliced Data")
    plt.xlabel(f'{feature}')
    plt.ylabel("Event Counts")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

if the observed data is true background data then we expect that approximately the same percentage of data would be remain after splitting as we found when splitting the QCD data.From the plots we can see that the high luminosity data approximately follows the distribution of signal + background for all of the feature cuts.

After making our cuts, we can find our expected signal-free distribution as a Poisson distribution which a mean of the ratio of remaining and initial background counts applied to the starting number of observed counts. We then find the significance of finding the counts remaining of the observation after making the same cuts if that background distribution is what we expect with no signal.

Part 3 - 95% Confidence Level of signal yields¶

To calculate this upper limit we first must construct a 2D histogram of the data after feature selection has been applied.

In [141]:
draw_number = 20000000
bkgd = stats.poisson.rvs(parameter, size=draw_number)
signal = stats.uniform.rvs(loc=0, scale=70, size=draw_number)
observed = bkgd + signal
signaledges = np.linspace(0,20,20)
dataedges = np.linspace(0,30,30)

Psd, temp, temp2= np.histogram2d(observed,signal, bins=[dataedges,signaledges], density=True)

datacenters = (dataedges[:-1] + dataedges[1:]) / 2
signalcenters = (signaledges[:-1] + signaledges[1:]) / 2
plt.pcolormesh(datacenters,signalcenters,Psd.T, shading='auto')
plt.axvline(24, color='red', linestyle='--', label='Observed value')

plt.ylabel('True signal, $P(s|d)$', fontsize = 24)
plt.xlabel('Observed data, $P(d|s)$', fontsize = 24)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

To calculate the 95% confidence interval we try to answer the question :-

What smallest signal can I have in order to claim that 95% of the time I would have seen the Higgs provided that signal?

In [142]:

plt.ylabel('Probability')
plt.show()

We can say that the probability distribution for the True signal has a poisson distribution with parameter as 11.5

So for the expected background as 14:

our expected 95% upper limit is:

We found that our expected value is slightly higher than our found value.This is due to the fact that the parameter for the probability of true signal is slightly lower that the expected data points for low luminosity.
